      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sponge",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 180°C conventional. Grease two 20 cm sandwich tins and line the bases with baking paper. Use the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "creaming method",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "creaming method",
                  "termId": "cmp6kpkd50000r8v4ph4e5wbq"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ": beat the butter and sugar for 5 minutes until very pale and light. Beat in the eggs one at a time, adding a spoonful of flour with each egg after the second to prevent curdling. Fold in the remaining flour and baking powder. Stir in the vanilla and enough milk to bring the batter to a slow dropping consistency. Divide evenly between the tins and smooth the tops.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake and cool",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake for 22 to 25 minutes until the sponge springs back when pressed lightly in the centre and a skewer comes out clean. Do not open the oven door before 20 minutes. Leave in the tins for 5 minutes, then turn out onto a rack and leave to cool completely before filling. Filling a warm sponge melts the buttercream.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the buttercream and assemble",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beat the butter until soft and pale. Beat in the icing sugar in two additions, then the vanilla and milk. The buttercream should be smooth and spreadable but hold a peak. Place one cooled sponge on a cake stand or plate. Spread the jam over the surface, then spread the buttercream over the jam. Set the second sponge on top, gently pressing down to level. Dust with icing sugar to finish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
